      "summary": "Treated a line ending in '=' (an unfinished assignment like 'let x =') as continuing onto the next line, because the language spec's own example says it should, even though its formal list of continuation triggers leaves '=' out.",
      "detail": "The grammar's closed table of newline-continuation triggers lists the binary/ternary operators (+ - * / % == != etc.), a trailing comma, an open bracket, and a leading operator — '=' is not in that list. But the spec's worked example, stated word-for-word in two places, says 'let x =\n\n  foo' is one statement equal to 'let x = foo', which only holds if a trailing '=' continues the line, and the spec also frames continuation as happening whenever 'the parser cannot otherwise close' the statement. I made a trailing '=' a continuation trigger (not a leading one) to honour the normative example, and did not edit the spec because the example is itself normative and the framing covers it."
